		<font size="2" face="Verdana">
		<font size="1" face="Verdana">posted 7/5/2000 8:28:00 AM&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;

		
		<a href="mailto:faeydrautha@aol.com" target="_new">
		<img src="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/email.gif" border="0" alt="Click Here to Email Gamer" width="24" height="11"></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
		
		<a href="MB_editmsg.asp?FID=62&FN=Druid&SID=7&SN=EverQuest&TID=418266&TN=Charging+for+tp+%21%21%21%21&CAT=Classes&SURL=http%3A%2F%2Fwww%2Eeverlore%2Ecom&MSID=418275&PL=4">
		<img src="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/edit.gif" border="0" alt="Edit/Delete Message" width="18" height="13"></a>
		
		</font>
		<hr size="1">Since posting my original message on this topic two things have changed that have modified my attitude.<P>1) I'm broke and will not be able to afford the bulk of my 29th level spells when I do eventually level.<P>2) Several very rude people have asked me for SoW, Buffs, heals and even TP's.  Two people in particular were so rude I confronted them.  The first guy denied being rude.  I’ll let you be the judge. <P>I was banking in Freeport when he ran up behind me and said, “Need heal”.  I was in a middle of a transaction, so I said, “I’m busy, and when I’m done I’ll heal you”.  He response was “heal pls”.  I stated more firmly, “Give me a minute, when I’m done I’ll heal you”.  He then went outside to wait.  After I concluded my business I went out where he was mediating and started to heal him.  After casting heal the second time he asked me if I’d run an errand for him.  I started to reply when I he very quickly responded to the fact I stopped casting heal on him with,  “continue healing”.  I immediately started to delete what I was typing, which incidentally was agreeing to run his errand, when another response from him came through, “What?  Can’t you heal?”  At that point I had had enough.  I told him to forget everything and I left.  However, he wasn’t done yet.  He sent me a tell asking why I stopped.  I had to then explain to him that he was rude and he could heal himself and run his own errand.  He actually asked me how he was rude.  I just told him to scroll up and read what he had written.<P>The second person didn’t even bother to deny it.  When confronted he simply laughed about it and replied “I know!”<P>Basically I agree with what most of you already wrote about this topic.  Everquest is a fantasy role-playing game.  The world of Norrath has an economy.  We are players portraying people within this world.  Some of us are wealthy, so of us are poor.  Some of us use trade skills to make money while others rely on hunting.  What is wrong with using our spells the way others use their trade skills to make money?  I don’t think I’ll charge all the time.  It depends on the circumstances.  If I decide when I reach 29th level to buy only the group gates spells and then spend the rest of the afternoon offering my services as a group gater in exchange for coin, what is so wrong about that?  I’m broke; I can provide a service to other players, if they have the coin to spend, why the hell not?  Why should I be looked down upon or insulted for this?<P>I have no intention of charging for my services when with a group.  That would just be stupid.  I will not charge when a nice person walks up to me and asks for a SoW.  I may have to refuse, depending on the situation, but I won’t charge.  I will continue to accept donations for anything and everything a person asks of me, but that is up to the player asking not me.  However, if I decide to setup shop for a period of time offering TP services for 10pp or 20pp a seat, then that is what I will do and I won’t be made to feel greedy for doing it.<P>As far as a possible charging system goes.  I will probably work it out based on the level of the person.  Higher levels can afford more and are probably doing it just to save themselves time.  Lower level characters have less coin and traveling can be too dangerous for them between certain zones.  For corpse retrieve it will always be free.<P>Gamer <BR><br>&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;<br></font>
	</font>
	</td>
